tory inadequacies related to environmental assessment, land-use planning, and emissions controls. Her detailed analysis situates these policy dynamics within the historical and global context of late-stage petro-capitalism and deepening neoliberalization of environmental policy. Fossilized reveals a country out of step with the transition unfolding in response to the climate crisis. As the global community moves toward decarbonization, Canada’s petro-provinces are instead doubling down on oil – to their ecological and economic peril.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnvironmental policyzAlberta. 0aEnvironmental policyzNewfoundland and Labrador. 0aEnvironmental policyzSaskatchewan. 0aPetroleum industry and tradezAlberta. 0aPetroleum industry and tradezNewfoundland and Labrador. 0aPetroleum industry and tradezSaskatchewan. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh1 aWynn, Graeme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311141765340uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486354440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774863544423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774863544/original  a978-3-11-127253-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127473-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-141765-3  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles